<h2>What Is Maladaptive Perfectionism?</h2>
<p>There's a meaningful distinction between high standards — a healthy drive to do things well — and perfectionism, which involves standards that are rigid, excessive, and contingently tied to self-worth. Maladaptive perfectionism is characterised by:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Standards that are unrealistic and that shift upward the moment they're met</li>
  <li>Self-worth that hinges almost entirely on achievement and performance</li>
  <li>Intense fear of failure, mistakes, or criticism</li>
  <li>Severe self-criticism when standards aren't met (which is often)</li>
  <li>Procrastination, paradoxically — avoidance driven by fear that the work won't be good enough</li>
  <li>Difficulty finishing work (it's never quite right)</li>
</ul>

<h2>What Perfectionism Actually Costs</h2>
<p>Perfectionism is associated with significantly higher rates of anxiety, depression, burnout, eating disorders, and OCD. It predicts academic and professional success in some domains but extracts a significant psychological toll — and often eventually impedes performance itself through procrastination, decision paralysis, and burnout.</p>

<p>Perfectionism also damages relationships. The same critical standards applied to oneself tend to be applied to others. Perfectionists often find it difficult to delegate, tolerate imperfection in partners or colleagues, or accept that others' standards may be different without being wrong.</p>

<h2>The Cognitive Core of Perfectionism</h2>
<p>Perfectionism is maintained by specific cognitive patterns:</p>

<p><strong>Conditional self-worth:</strong> "I am only valuable when I am performing excellently." This makes failure or mediocrity feel existentially threatening rather than merely disappointing.</p>

<p><strong>Dichotomous thinking:</strong> "If it's not perfect, it's a failure." There's no adequate middle ground, which means most outcomes are coded as failures.</p>

<p><strong>Selective attention:</strong> Perfectionists disproportionately notice mistakes and discount successes — even when objectively their performance is excellent. The focus is always on what fell short.</p>

<p><strong>Cost-benefit reversal:</strong> The focus on mistakes generates more distress than success generates satisfaction, creating a chronically negative experience of achievement.</p>

<h2>Evidence-Based Treatment</h2>

<h3>CBT for Perfectionism</h3>
<p>Roz Shafran and colleagues developed a specific CBT protocol for perfectionism with strong evidence. It addresses the cognitive patterns above alongside behavioural experiments — deliberately performing to a "good enough" standard and observing the actual consequences, which are rarely as catastrophic as feared. Reducing checking and safety behaviours (re-reading work repeatedly, seeking excessive reassurance) is part of treatment.</p>

<h3>Compassion-Focused Therapy (CFT)</h3>
<p>CFT directly addresses the intense self-criticism at the heart of perfectionism. It develops self-compassion — not complacency, but the ability to respond to failure and imperfection with kindness rather than harsh criticism. This is not natural for most perfectionists and requires deliberate practice, but the evidence is compelling.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<p><strong>Won't treating my perfectionism make me less motivated?</strong><br/>
This is the most common fear and the most consistently disconfirmed. Reducing perfectionism consistently improves performance — by reducing procrastination, burnout, and the emotional weight of work. Many clients find they achieve more after reducing perfectionism, not less.</p>

<p><strong>Is perfectionism linked to childhood?</strong><br/>
Often. Perfectionism frequently develops in environments where love, approval, or safety felt conditional on performance. Therapy addresses these origins alongside current patterns.</p>

<p><strong>How long does treatment take?</strong><br/>
CBT for perfectionism is typically 8–16 sessions. Deeper schema-level work around conditional self-worth may take longer. Most people see meaningful improvement within a 12-week course.</p>

